---
import Layout from "@/layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout>
  <main class="min-h-screen bg-zinc-50 font-sans text-zinc-900">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-2xl px-4 py-10">
      <h1 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-zinc-900">
        How Zip works
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-2 text-zinc-600">
        Zip is a path puzzle: connect waypoints in order and fill every cell. No
        accounts, no server storing your game—everything lives in a shareable
        link. Here's how to create, play, and what to expect.
      </p>

      <section class="mt-10">
        <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-zinc-800">
          How to create a puzzle
        </h2>
        <ol class="mt-3 list-inside list-decimal space-y-2 text-zinc-600">
          <li>
            Go to <a
              href="/play/zip/create"
              class="text-emerald-600 hover:underline">Create</a
            > and pick a grid size (4×4 up to 8×8).
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Draw the path</strong> by tapping or dragging through every non-blocked
            cell. You can mark some cells as blocked (they stay dark).
          </li>
          <li>
            When the path is complete, switch to <strong>Place waypoints</strong
            > and put numbers 1, 2, 3, … on the path in order. Waypoint 1 must be
            on the start of the path and the last number on the end.
          </li>
          <li>
            Click <strong>Create game link</strong>. You get a single link that
            contains the whole puzzle (and the creator's solution for checking).
            The link is valid for 24 hours.
          </li>
          <li>
            You also get a <strong>game seed</strong>. If the link expires,
            anyone with the seed can recreate the same puzzle on the Create page
            (Import game seed) and get a new link.
          </li>
        </ol>
      </section>

      <section class="mt-10">
        <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-zinc-800">How to play</h2>
        <ol class="mt-3 list-inside list-decimal space-y-2 text-zinc-600">
          <li>
            Open the game link (from the creator or a friend who already
            played).
          </li>
          <li>
            Enter your name and start. You only get <strong
              >one attempt per link</strong
            >—no do-overs with the same name.
          </li>
          <li>
            Draw a path that visits waypoints 1 → 2 → … in order and fills every
            non-blocked cell. Tap or drag on the grid.
          </li>
          <li>
            When you finish, your score (moves and time) is saved into the link.
            You'll see a <strong>new link</strong>—that's the same game plus
            your result. Share that link so others can play and see the updated
            scoreboard.
          </li>
        </ol>
      </section>

      <section class="mt-10">
        <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-zinc-800">
          How the link (and scoreboard) works
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-zinc-600">
          The link is a <strong>stateless chain</strong>: the full game state
          (puzzle, creator solution, and every player's score and path) is
          encoded in the URL. There is no central server storing “this game.”
          When someone opens the link, their browser decodes it and shows the
          current scoreboard. When a new person plays, they submit their result
          and get back an updated link that includes their entry. So the
          "scoreboard" is whatever is inside the link you're looking at.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3 text-zinc-600">
          <strong>Important:</strong> you don't see live updates. You only see the
          scores (and solutions) of people whose <strong>updated link</strong> you
          have. If Alice plays and shares her new link with the group, everyone who
          opens that link sees Alice's score. If Bob plays next and shares his link,
          that link includes both Alice and Bob—but people who only have Alice's link
          won't see Bob until someone shares the latest link. So the "next person's
          score” isn’t visible to you until they (or someone else) share the link
          that contains their result.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="mt-10">
        <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-zinc-800">
          Downsides and trade-offs
        </h2>
        <ul class="mt-3 list-inside list-disc space-y-2 text-zinc-600">
          <li>
            <strong>No live scoreboard.</strong> You only see scores that are in the
            link you opened. To see who played after you, someone must share the latest
            game link.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>One play per person per game.</strong> Your name is tied to one
            solution; you can't replay with the same link.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Links expire after 24 hours.</strong> After that, the puzzle is
            read-only (you can still view results). Use the <strong
              >game seed</strong
            > to recreate the same puzzle and get a new link.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Long URLs.</strong> The more players, the longer the link. Fine
            for sharing in chat or groups; not ideal for typing by hand.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="mt-10">
        <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-zinc-800">
          Made to play with friends
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-zinc-600">
          Zip is built for a small group of friends. One person creates a puzzle
          and shares the link. Everyone plays and then shares their <strong
            >completed</strong
          > link back into the group (e.g. in a WhatsApp group, Discord, or thread).
          Each time someone shares the latest link, the whole group can open it and
          see the full scoreboard and who found a different ("Novel") solution. You
          compare scores and solutions by passing around the same evolving link—no
          accounts, no app, just one link that gets updated as people play. It's a
          bit like a chain letter: the game grows as each friend adds their result
          and shares it forward.
        </p>
      </section>

      <nav class="mt-12 flex flex-wrap gap-4 border-t border-zinc-200 pt-8">
        <a
          href="/play/zip/create"
          class="rounded-lg bg-emerald-600 px-4 py-2 text-sm font-medium text-white hover:bg-emerald-500"
        >
          Create a puzzle
        </a>
        <a
          href="/play/zip"
          class="rounded-lg border border-zinc-300 bg-white px-4 py-2 text-sm font-medium text-zinc-700 hover:bg-zinc-50"
        >
          Play (with a link)
        </a>
        <a href="/" class="text-sm text-zinc-500 hover:underline">Home</a>
      </nav>
    </div>
  </main>
</Layout>
